My problem:  Every time I go where people here tell me I find no consistent difficulty.  New Yorker, LA Times et al.

All seems pretty hit or miss.

@Andrzej

I am by no means the expert on women's clothing stores, but I believe the MISSES department is for young women, i.e., the unmarried "Miss".

I think this is usually tweens and young teens.

@CCNY

This is all so alien to me! Over here in a dress shop the dresses are sorted by brand and style, mostly, and by size within these categories. Age never comes into it, at all. I mean, why would it? Women of all ages wear whatever they want these days, and there are both very small mature women and well built teens. To me, sorting dresses by age seems almost discriminatory, and certainly judgy.

A garment store having a kid's section is the only age-related arrangement here.

@Andrzej
Generall used to describe a person who seems totally uninvolved in what everyone else is supposed to be doing, like group work. Generally used in the term, "about as useful as a bump on a log."  
Hope this helps.

@Jane Wheelaghan

It is common practice for two students to share a room in American universities.  Incoming freshmen almost always get a share automatically; some schools that have a housing shortage even put three in a room, using bunk beds for two of them.  Upperclassmen can sometimes get single rooms, but many move off-campus for that perk.

Fancier colleges may have different setups, but not in the decidedly unfancy ones my kids attended not long ago.

@Steve L
The sheer volume of students in the US must make a difference. In 1970 only about 8% of young people went to university in the UK, 19% in 1990, and it's about 40% now so there has been a lot of building. Lots of universities don't have accommodation near the main buildings, not many have a 'campus'.

Private companies have built student accommodation - purpose-built flats for 6 sharing (single rooms) and mixed-sex, not always near the university.

@Lewis

If MILLET reminds you of Millay, you may be the kind of consumer who shops at "Tar-zhay".

On the other hand, any excuse to do a deep dive into a wonderful poet is a good one.

@Lewis
I hope we're all familiar with The Armadillo Song by Flanders & Swann. If not, go listen to it right now. I can confidently state that it is the only appearance of 'theodolite' in a popular song. For that alone I would love it.

"Listen to my armadillo roundelay..."

@Times Rita

I'm betting you couldn't get a charango like that through Customs these days.

On the other hand, if you had learned to play "Tom DOOLEY" on the charango, I'd bet Peter Seeger would've brought you on-stage for the sing-along.

@The X-Phile

Funny, but to me "turtle-rabbit" could only be one animal, so that clue was a complete gimme. Like way, way too many others on a Friday.

Happy you enjoyed it, and the grid itself was fine.

@Rich in Atlanta
Did anyone ever do the companion piece, From Right to Left?
