@Matt
I'm a strict constructionist. No lookups, no aids from Wordplay, no checking the completed grid. Any of those counts as a cheat for me and I break my streak.
Sometimes I will bewail my weakness here  and confess my waywardness. No absolution expected.

@Grant
Tom Dooley is a favorite to play at bluegrass jams. Check out Doc Watson’s version and you’ll understand. 

Another very popular one, believe it or not, is Glendale Train by NRPS. Nine Pound Hammer also ranks up there.

@Amy 
baguette: 2a; a gem cut in the form of a narrow rectangle. 
  – American Heritage Dictionary

@jennie

How do you know that’s not the case? They turn down dozens of puzzles all the time for lots of reasons, which can include difficulty.
Moreover, please understand that the main issue with difficulty has to do with clueing which is in the editors’ hands. We don’t know which clues are the constructors’ and which the editors’, but they can and do ratchet the difficulty up and down as they see fit. I have nothing against this grid. I just get mad when I see a ton of gimme clues or easy crosses that really don’t present much of a challenge to solvers with even moderate experience.

@Matt

I believe Niall was aiming for an instance of the “hold my beer while I lampoon all the people commenting about how easy this puzzle was for them” genre of comment.

As someone who is a certified, pitchfork-carrying member of the “too easy” crowd, I don’t tend to find such comments very entertaining, unless they’re especially well executed (very rare). But anyhoo, that’s what this is…

@Anonymous
For me the weekends vary between hard and nigh on impossible so it doesn’t make much difference, but people are entitled to their opinions on the difficulty.

I’m probably very Irish in that we do not like what we regard as boasting.  There is good and bad to that aspect of our culture and to be honest I’d be better off ignoring it.

